 Compute $\arccos \left (-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right).$  Express your answer in radians. The final Answer is \frac{3 \pi}{4}
 ### Proof
 Since $\cos \frac{3 \pi}{4} = -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}},$ $\arccos \left( -\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \right) = \boxed{\frac{3 \pi}{4}}.$
 *)

theorem
fixes x :: real
assumes h0 : "x = - 1 / sqrt 2"
shows  "arccos x = 3 * pi / 4"
 proof- 
  show ?thesis sledgehammer
